 To find the common difference of this arithmetic sequence, we can subtract the second term from the ninth term. So, the common difference \(d\) can be calculated as \(d = 30 - 2\). </think> Let's calculate it.
\begin{align*}
d &= 30 - 2\\
&= 28
\end{align*}
Now, let's use the formula for the \(n\)th term of an arithmetic sequence, \(a_n = a_1 + (n-1)d\), to find the first term. We know that the second term \(a_2 = 2\), so we can set up the equation \(2 = a_1 + d\).
\begin{align*}
2 &= a_1 + 28\\
a_1 &= 2 - 28\\
a_1 &= -26
\end{align*}
Next, we use the formula again with \(n = 50\) to find the fiftieth term.
\begin{align*}
a_{50} &= a_1 + (50-1)d\\
&= -26 + 28 \times 49\\
&= -26 + 1372\\
&= 1346
\end{align*}
So, the fiftieth term is 1346.

